TY  - JOUR
T1  - From Ritual to Reality: Demography, Ideology, and Decoupling in a Post-Communist Government Agency
AU  - Tilcsik, András
Y1  - 2010/12/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.57318905
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.57318905
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1474
EP  - 1498
VL  - 53
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Decoupling?the creation of gaps between formal policies and actual practices?is ubiquitous in organizations. Yet little research has examined how decoupling unfolds over time. This qualitative case study of a post-Communist government agency develops process models of what precedes and what follows the decision to decouple. I show that the demography and ideology of powerful organization members influence whether decoupling occurs, how it unfolds, and whether it is sustainable. Further, I suggest decoupling may carry seeds of its own decay: under certain conditions, the decision to decouple can trigger demographic changes that eventually erode decoupling.
AB  - Decoupling?the creation of gaps between formal policies and actual practices?is ubiquitous in organizations. Yet little research has examined how decoupling unfolds over time. This qualitative case study of a post-Communist government agency develops process models of what precedes and what follows the decision to decouple. I show that the demography and ideology of powerful organization members influence whether decoupling occurs, how it unfolds, and whether it is sustainable. Further, I suggest decoupling may carry seeds of its own decay: under certain conditions, the decision to decouple can trigger demographic changes that eventually erode decoupling.
