TY  - JOUR
T1  - Building Sustainable Hybrid Organizations: The Case of Commercial Microfinance Organizations
AU  - Battilana, Julie
AU  - Dorado, Silvia
Y1  - 2010/12/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.57318391
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.57318391
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1419
EP  - 1440
VL  - 53
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We explore how new types of hybrid organizations (organizations that combine institutional logics in unprecedented ways) can develop and maintain their hybrid nature in the absence of a ?ready-to-wear? model for handling the tensions between the logics they combine. The results of our comparative study of two pioneering commercial microfinance organizations suggest that to be sustainable, new types of hybrid organizations need to create a common organizational identity that strikes a balance between the logics they combine. Our evidence further suggests that the crucial early levers for developing such an organizational identity among organization members are hiring and socialization policies.
AB  - We explore how new types of hybrid organizations (organizations that combine institutional logics in unprecedented ways) can develop and maintain their hybrid nature in the absence of a ?ready-to-wear? model for handling the tensions between the logics they combine. The results of our comparative study of two pioneering commercial microfinance organizations suggest that to be sustainable, new types of hybrid organizations need to create a common organizational identity that strikes a balance between the logics they combine. Our evidence further suggests that the crucial early levers for developing such an organizational identity among organization members are hiring and socialization policies.
