TY  - JOUR
T1  - Formal Dining at Cambridge Colleges: Linking Ritual Performance and Institutional Maintenance
AU  - Dacin, M. Tina
AU  - Munir, Kamal
AU  - Tracey, Paul
Y1  - 2010/12/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.57318388
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.57318388
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1393
EP  - 1418
VL  - 53
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examine the role of rituals in institutional maintenance. Through an in-depth, qualitative study of formal dining at the University of Cambridge, we explore how the performance of these rituals contributes to the maintenance of the British class system. We find that rituals are important for institutional maintenance because they have a powerful bearing on participants beyond the confines of the rituals themselves. Our analysis also suggests that institutions are refracted through context and individual experience at a micro level, and indicates a more fragmented and less strategic conception of institutional maintenance than is portrayed in recent work.
AB  - We examine the role of rituals in institutional maintenance. Through an in-depth, qualitative study of formal dining at the University of Cambridge, we explore how the performance of these rituals contributes to the maintenance of the British class system. We find that rituals are important for institutional maintenance because they have a powerful bearing on participants beyond the confines of the rituals themselves. Our analysis also suggests that institutions are refracted through context and individual experience at a micro level, and indicates a more fragmented and less strategic conception of institutional maintenance than is portrayed in recent work.
